review_blob: Tap at dangerous man. I wanted to believe that dangerous man had figured out how to brew on his equipment, but alas, that is not the case. This beer is severely under attenuated. It smells nice enough, but the first sip is tastes only like a pack of smarties. This beer and the dogwood porter were too sweet. Its too bad as I really wanted to like this beer.

This is a joke, right? One of the employees described this as, "grain belt but spicier" to a customer. He was pretty damn close, as Id say it was just a clone of nordeast. Malty beer that had a light toffee and caramel character. The guy lied as there is no spice present. Taste is somewhere between a Vienna lager and a brown ale. This is a saison in name alone.
Dear lord this cider is terrible. It got better as it warmed, but hop profile was very out of place. Skip it.
This is a poor excuse of a saison, and a poorer version of a lime beer. Dont waste your time here.

I stumbled into a local cantina in the university of Minnesota area of Minneapolis and asked for something local. The lovely bartender slid a Rona light across the bar, and quickly tossed me 3 limes. Rona light lime lime lime she said. I was hooked. This beer stinks of fresh citrus. The lime character you would love to encounter on a lonely island. Tastes like the best bud light lime you could ever taste. Fresh, crisp, resinous. You know what I mean. I pounded a few of these tonight.

First beer I had from 612.  Does the 6 run by here?  Awful beer.  Malt forward and barely any hop presence.  How is anyone giving this a review over 3?  This beer is crap.  Once again they make a beer that one can barely smell.  As far as taste goes this is malty, and I cant get any hop character at all.

Second beer I tried from 612.  Looks brown in the pint glass t is served in.  Pretty damn bland tasting.  Watery and thin, slight roast character towards the finish, and there was nothing in between.  I wish I had more to say, but this is boring, thin, and bad.  Skip it if you are in town.

Dont know how I never rated this beer as Ive had it many times and always love it.  Can into glass.  Dark black in color with a small head.  The color and consistency of the head reminds me of a dark chocolate hot chocolate.  Almost creamy looking.  Bad ass looking to say the least.  Loads of chocolate in the aroma.  Some plum and roasted barley are also present.  Very nice stuff thus far.  Its the taste and texture that really nail it for me with this beer.  Tons of dark chocolate through out this beers flavor.  Some oats and barley are also present before this ends finishes slightly dry with a nice bit of bitterness.  Could be the hops as it seems to have a little fruity character in the finish as well.  Fucking awesome!  This has a creamy body that really makes this beer shine.  Not many imperial stouts are on this level with the texture (Im looking at speedway, darkness, and expo).  I may need to run to Wisconsin to grab another can of this to toss into a beef and barley soup I want to make this weekend.

Bottle shared by atom.  Hazy, orange apricot color.  Not the prettiest lambic.  A good amount of apricot present in the aroma.  Tart, slight bile character, maybe a it of moldy cheese.  Wow.  This may be my favorite fruit lambic.  Loads of apricot flavor, slight acidity towards the finish.  I love the balance and the big apricot flavor.

Bottle sent by an amazing secret Santa.  I honestly never thought Id get the chance to try this, so thank you for sending this bottle Santa.  Lightly hazy, orange in color, and a small, fluffy, white head sits on top.  Fruity aroma, with a little dustiness, and a bit of funk.  Not as tart as I had anticipated, but not that isnt neccisarily bad.  Good amount of sourness and acidity upfront with some lemon, some yogurt character towards the finish.  Nice puckering finish that goes on forever.  Really, really good beer, and Im happy to share this with a couple good buddies and the girlfriend.
beer_name: 3 Fonteinen J & J Oude Geuze Blauw

review_blob: Bottle.  Hazy, lemon yellow color with some scarce bubbles around the rim of my glass.  Citrus filled aroma.  Best of the bunch so far.  Lots of grapefruit, candied oranges, and decently bitter.

Bottle.  Hazy orange color with minimal head.  This is almost murky looking.  Light aroma that doesnt have much going on.  Maybe some lemon.  Sweet tasting with a little bit of lemon and grass.  The second sip was much better than the first.  Not my cup of tea.

Bottle from Santa.  First beer of the golden globes.  Lightly hazy orange/yellow color with a small whitehead.  Loads of carbonation in this beer.  Citrus filled aroma with lots of orange, lime, grapefruit, lemon zest, and bit of pine.  Pretty incredible.  Taste is interesting but not as good asthe aroma.  Candied citrus, slight lemon, grassiness. and caramel sweetness.  Dry finish.

Can.  Hazy mahogany color with a small, off white head.  I dont know what this is upon first look and sip. Adam tells me this is a brown.

Smells like old caramels.  I know many people are thinking "what do old caramels mell like?"  Dust and caramel.

Im missing the rich aspects of a brown ale with this beer.  Thin, and watery, body.  Hoppier hn most browns.  Just not enthused.

Bottle of batch 2 shared by atom.  Cola brown in color with no visible head.  Caramely sweet aroma.  Slight whiskey character.  Taste nice.  Lots of toffee and caramel, slight vanilla, and a little bit of heat on the finish.  The rye is subtle.  I can dig this, but I like before the dawn much better.

Bottle poured to my friends navel.  Perfect pour.  Cheese filled aroma.  I really cant describe more than that.  No blueberry present.  Blueberry is upfront but fades quickly.  Slight acidity towards the finish.  Suck a dick Minnesota.

Bottle.  Black in color with a small khaki head.  Looks like a dark tomme that also smells better.  Smells like blackberries.  Im drunk, but damn this tastes delicious.  Boys, this is better than a shit hawk hitting a shitfan.

Bottle.  Clear raspberry jam color with a small white head.  Clear raspberry character in the aroma, some cherry, light sugar aspect, some vinegar.  Sweeter taste as the raspberries have fallen off.  The finish has a good dose of raspberry tartness with a small acetic vinegar punch that makes my mouth water.  Not much body to this, and its pretty dull until the finish.  I should have drank this fresh.

Opened this up before I realized it was 13% alcohol.  Wow, this looks incredible.  Clear, ruby color, with no head.  Smells like gummy candy and booze.  I love gummies but the booze is a bit much.  Oh my god this is sweet!  Cloying, sticky, too much.  Drain pour.

Bottle from a trade some time ago.  Been seeing some more positive reviews lately so I figured Id pop it open.  Muddy brown color that has some slight ruby highlights.  Light candy cherry aroma that lacks the punch of the regular barrel select.  Light cherry flavor, a bit thin and seltzer like, lit tannic barrel character.  Not digging this after beatification.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Bottle.  Muddy brown color with a small off white head.  Sour aroma with slight cherry notes.  Slight toffee character too.  Not too complex, but it is better than how it tastes.  Taste is sour but that is really it.  I want to like it more, but its very one dimensional.

Batch 1.  Dark brown color with a medium sized dark khaki head.  Lots of graham cracker in the aroma with a touch of raisin.  Pretty mediocre to be frank.  Pretty dry, slightly smokey as the roast character is over the top.  That smokey character dominates everything else.  I wish something else was going on.

Growler.  Deep brown color with just a whisp of khaki colored bubbles.  Aroma is surprisingly filled with Christmas spices.  Clove, all spice, chocolate in the aroma.  Pretty well balanced.  Lightly spiced flavor and is mainly chocolate and roast coffee.  Medium bodied with a lightly roasted malt finish.  Pretty interesting, but I see this as being more of a beer I would want paired with food.

Bottle.  Black in color with a small khaki head.  Very thick looking.  Smells like graham cracker, vanilla, raisin, prune, slight bourbon, and chocolate.  Slightly thin texture with vanilla, chocolate, bourbon, and marshmallow.  Drinks like its ABV.  Big burn in the finish.  This is pretty rough.

Poured from a smartwater bottle.  Pretty damn dark brown in color with a khaki head.  Super chocolate forward aroma, plenty of roast coffee, and a touch of piney hops.  Taste is very similar with more roast coffee, slightly less chocolate, and pine hops in the finish.  Thick, chalky texture with a long lasting finish.  Definitely enjoyed this one.

Bottle.  Slight haze to this and a small white.  Orange, grapefruit, nectarine, and caramel all present in the aroma.  A bit malt ire than I remember.  Taste is well balanced between sweet caramel and bread malts, and plenty of orange and nectarine fruitiness.  Slight resinous hop character, but not as big and brash as some apas have become.  Nice medium body.  Really enjoyable stuff.

Bottle opened with a small gush, but the the pour was surprisingly very foamy.  The medium sized, white head died pretty quickly after the pour.  Nice citric tartness, sweet wheat, light fruitiness in the aroma.  Definitely get the pineapple that they were talking about, with a lot of citrus and lemon present as well.  Lightly tart taste, plenty of wheat character, lemon seltzer, and plenty of citrus.  Very light bodied, and considering the style this is really great.  Very enjoyable.

Its that time of year when I really enjoy a good stout, so this is something that Im looking forward to trying.  Poured from a bottle into a tulip.  Brown in color with a small khaki head.  A bit lighter in color than I prefer for my stouts.  Very fruity aroma with notes of raisins and dark cherries, and a solid roasted coffee scent, with a little bit of dark chocolate.  So far the nose on this is great.  Taste is pretty damn thin.  Light chocolate, thin coffee, and a strange finish that has a beef jerky quality.  Metallic in the finish as well.  Im really put off by how this tastes.

Bottle I brought back from Wisconsin to share with some friends.  Clear, dark red in color with a slight purple note.  Small foamy cap on top that has a light salmon color.  Aroma is well balanced between the cherry and cranberry, with a little bit of apple.  Really wonderful to smell.  Taste is balanced between apple, cranberry, and the cherries.  Maybe a bit more cranberry and tart apple than the cherries.  I pronounced tartness to this beer.  Absolutely wonderful fruit beer, that I prefer to the Belgian Red.  The tart aspects really make this beer special when compared to the sweetness of many of the other fruit beers from New Glarus.

Bottle shared by atom.  I love me some IPAs, and this beer has plenty of hype, so hopefully it lives up to my expectations.  Clear, copper orange color with a nice, frothy white head.  Grapefruit, orange, light fruit in the aroma.  Reminds me a bit of Two Hearted to be honest.  Fairly bitter with lots of grapefruit.  The bitterness is a tad much for me.  I wish there was a touch more malt character to help balance this out.  This is a pretty damn good beer, but it reminds me too much of Two Hearted.  I guess that isnt a bad thing but I find Two Hearted to be more balanced and much more accessible locally.

Growler.  Deep, dark brown color that flirts with black in color.  Dark khaki head sits on top.  Aroma has blackberries, blueberries, chocolate, plenty of roast coffee, but there is some slight green pepper.  Taste is roast coffee, chocolate, slightly smokey.  Wow.  Good shit.  Pretty rich, hefty body.  Glad to share this with some close friends.
beer_name: Pizza Boy Sunny Side Up - Double Coffee

review_blob: Ive enjoyed the majority of beers that Ive had from Maine brewing, so hearing that this was a part of a recent trade I was pretty excited.  Deep brown in color with a nice khaki head.  Looks promising.  Aroma has tobacco and chocolate.  Pretty damn hoppy for a porter.  Chocolate, light grapefruit, tobacco, and a dry finish.  Damn solid offering from Maine again.

Growler shared with atom.  Clear straw color with a small white head.  Aroma is strong sourdough.  Makes me wish I was still baking bread.  Doughy, slight tartness.  Really nice so far.  Oh god this tastes great.  Nice tart finish, sourdough bread flavor, a touch of lemon.  Delicious, light, clean and crisp finish.  Killer stuff.  I want more tired hands beers!

Bottle.  Cloudy gold with a small white head.  This destroys the previous barley wine I had.  Big pine and citrus hop aroma.  Smells great.  Taste is caramel forward with a lot of candied orange and grapefruit.  Really good hop forward barleywine.

Bottle.  Murky bronze in color with a small white head.  The aroma is pretty foul.  Toffee, chocolate, some dirty kitchen sink that hasnt been cleaned in weeks and has a small puddle of standing water.  Taste is better but it is very sugary.  Tastes like a boozy sugar baby candy.  Not too heavy of a body.  Pretty forgettable.

Bottle.  Hazy iced tea look to this.  How did I manage to get almost no head when pouring this beer?  Im not impressed with my pour.  A bit more sour and acidic smelling than what I normally get from jolly pumpkin beers.  Good amount of funky cheese, lemon, and raspberry.  Makes my nose tingle.  A bit thin bodied, but damn does it have a sour punch towards the finish.  Bile, raspberry, lots of acid.  Good.  Not as dry as most JP beers, and this focuses more on sour aspects.

Can.  Clear, straw/piss yellow color with a small white head.  Light floral and grassy aroma.  Some light fruit and a touch sweet.  Taste is light.  Slight apple, cereal malt, grass, but a strange metallic finish.  Light body and but that metallic finish is a huge turn off.

The third of the pannepots that Ive tried.  Slightly murky, dark brown in color, and a small slightly off white head.  Not the prettiest of beers.  Smells like the sweetest and booziest of the 3 variants I have tried.  Lots of fig, raisin, toffee, and caramel dominate the aroma.  Fairly boozy.  Pretty thin on the tongue, and pretty damn boozy.  Sweet candy sugar, caramel, and booze soaked raisins.  I absolutely love pannepot and the reserve, but this really isnt nearly as good.
beer_name: Struise Pannept - Old Monks Ale - Pannepeut

review_blob: Bottle.  Dark orange in color with a small white head.  It has a nice golden color when held up to the light.  There seems to be just a touch of haze in the beer as well.  Really nice aroma that mixes the yam character, with a little bit of fruitiness, and just a hint of nutmeg.  Everything is well integrated in the aroma, with nothing dominating more than any other characteristic.  Taste is sweet potato with a hint of nutmeg.  Very subtle.  Pretty light to medium bodied, and fairly refreshing when compared to others of the style.  This is an example of a spice beer that I enjoy which has more subtle spicing.  Usually I like aggressively spiced pumpkin beers (Weyerbacher Imperial Pumpkin Ale), but this does a great job being subtle and enjoyable.

Bottle.  Dark bronze in color with a medium sized white head.  Really interesting aroma that is reminiscent of whiskey.  Nice caramel and toffee aromas but there is a strange dust component.  It smells like an old house that hasnt been cleaned in a while.  Taste is bland.  Slight whiskey character towards the finish.  Not too impressed.

Somehow I have never rated this.  Bottle that started to vomit up a little bit of foam after I opened it.  Once it made it into my glass it had a deep brown color with a khaki head.  Some little flecks that look like cinnamon on a pumpkin spice coffee are resting atop the foam.  Really nice looking.  Tons of dark fruit in the aroma.  Raisins, figs, some green apple character, toffee, and caramel all present in the aroma.  Taste is rich with caramel and raisin.  Slight tart apple character still towards the finish.  Not too big and rich, as the strange tart character helps cut the big dark fruit flavors down.  I really enjoy this, and it reminds me of the Dolle Oerbier Reserva.

Bottle from Craig.  Clear apple juice color with fluffy white head.  Pretty nice head retention.  Slight orange aroma, plenty of floral character, and a slightly odd mint character.  Taste is malty with more floral hops.  Something is very off with the flavor to me.  I cant place my finger on it but something doesnt taste quite right to me.  Fairly bitter finish.

Bottle from pawola.  Hazy peach color with a small white head.  Loads of citrus and wheat in the aroma with some floral notes.  Taste is very citrus forward with light peach notes.  Good dose of grapefruit up front and in the finish, and a strong wheat character in this brew as well.  Pretty damn enjoyable for an American wheat beer, and the aggressive hopping really turns this in to a top notch beer.

Had this on tap at Darkness Day.  Ive been really enjoying brett IPAs lately.  When compared to Bitter Monk, the Rock Bottom Brett IPAs, and Brettwagon Id say this one falls a bit short.  Aroma is a sweeter with some pineapple and juicy fruit gum. There is a hint of grapefruit but it is pretty minimal.  Honestly, I dont get any brett in the aroma.  Taste is more tropical fruit forward, but it still has a great deal of sweetness.  I get a little bit of brett in the flavor of the beer but it is minimal.  This really comes off more like a belgian IPA, and less like a bretted IPA.  I really liked brettwagon when I had it, and while this is still pretty damn good I just didnt like it nearly as much.  It could also be that this beer never got a chance to open up in my glass as it was as cold as ryanfoltys vagina today at the Surly Brewery.

Bottle.  Deep, dark brown color with a small khaki head.  Looks really pretty incredible in the glass.  Smokey aroma, with some hints of the apple brandy barrel.  Lots of meaty goodness, some chocolate, and a hint of cherry.  Taste is chocolate heavy, salty bacon character, some cherry, slight apple, and a long dark chocolate finish.  I wish more of the barrel presence came through, but this is still an absolute monster of a beer.  Great silky mouthfeel.  Fucking great.
beer_name: Captain Lawrence Imperial Smoke from the Oak (Apple Brandy Barrel)

review_blob: Bottle.  Light copper in color with a medium sized, foamy, white head.  The look of this is pretty nice.  Great bit of citrus in the aroma, some lemon, but there is a strange cleaning solution note there as well.  If that cleaning shit wasnt there it would be a damn nice aroma.  Taste is grapefruit and a touch of lemon.  Finish tastes like what lemon pledge smells like.  I want to like this more but there are too many things that I cant get on board with..

Bottle from pawola.  Clear and golden in color with a small white head.  Juicy fruit aroma, and I mean the gum and not some fruits that you can squeeze loads of juice from.  Maybe a hint of orange there and a touch of grapefruit.  A bit thin and lacking of much flavor.  Pretty damn watery.  Slight juicy fruit flavor, but not much of it.

Pottle recommended to me by the beer warden.  Deep, dark brown with a small khaki head.  Rich chocolate and roast coffee aroma with some pumpkin, clove, nutmeg, and cinnamon in the background.  Pretty damn nice.  The flavor doesnt do as much for me.  Taste is pumpkin muffins and chocolate.  It doesnt come together for me.  Its a bit sweeter than I care for, but it is still pretty enjoyable.

Growler.  Aged precisely an equivalent amount of time to a rabbits gestation period.  This was done by the request of thome50.  He said this was when the beer was at its peak.  Pour is deep brown with a massive khaki head.  Great lacing left on the glass after the head dies down.  Sweet chocolate and coconut aroma.  Only time Ive ever had Vietnamese coffee was cold press, but this is very reminiscent.  Sweeter and more desert-like.  Taste has much more roast coffee character coming out, but it is a bit charred tasting to me.  Lots of sweetness with milk chocolate and coconut still being present.  Finish has some cherries.  Just like regular speedway this is full bodied, but not too heavy and rich.  Nice and silky on the tongue.  Pretty damn good, but the sweeter character is really not something I like.  Too much like desert coffee for me.
beer_name: AleSmith Speedway Stout - Brewers Blend: Vietnamese Coffee

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob:
Went international to land this hard to come by beer.  Thanks GTH for this awesome bottle.  Well be talking again soon, probably when Im drunk, just like last time.  

Deep brown in color with no head.  It looks as viscous as oil.  Im guessing if I dropped a lead musket in here it would still float.

Sweet, cream, milk chocolate, slight raisin are all present in the aroma.  Th raisin is definitely the lightest of all.

Cherry is definetely there in the taste,  The body on this is terrible.  Under carbonated and flabby.  I just dont like this that much.  Regular adam, and adam from the wood, are fantastic but this is now.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Cherry Adam from the Wood
